            <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-slate-900">Understanding NSW WHS Legislation</h1>
            <p class="mt-2 text-xl text-slate-600">An Interactive Guide to the Act, Regulation, and Codes of Practice</p>
        </header>

        <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md mb-8">
            <p class="text-lg text-slate-700">The Work Health and Safety (WHS) framework in New South Wales is built on three core components that work together. A simple way to understand their relationship is [1]:</p>
            <ul class="list-none mt-4 space-y-3">
                <li class="flex items-start">
                    <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold text-xl mr-3">1.</span>
                    <div>
                        <strong class="text-slate-800">The WHS Act 2011:</strong> This is the primary legislation that outlines the broad legal requirements and duties for workplace safety.[1]
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                    <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold text-xl mr-3">2.</span>
                    <div>
                        <strong class="text-slate-800">The WHS Regulation 2011:</strong> This provides the specific and detailed requirements for complying with the duties set out in the Act.[1, 2]
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                    <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold text-xl mr-3">3.</span>
                    <div>
                        <strong class="text-slate-800">Codes of Practice:</strong> These are practical, instructional guides on how to comply with the Regulation and the Act for specific tasks or hazards.[1, 3]
                    </div>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <main class="space-y-4">

            <details class="framework-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm overflow-hidden group">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer bg-white hover:bg-slate-100">
                    <div class="flex items-center">
                        <div class="bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full h-10 w-10 flex items-center justify-center mr-4">
                            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-6 w-6" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 6.253v13m0-13C10.832 5.477 9.246 5 7.5 5S4.168 5.477 3 6.253v13C4.168 18.477 5.754 18 7.5 18s3.332.477 4.5 1.253m0-13C13.168 5.477 14.754 5 16.5 5c1.747 0 3.332.477 4.5 1.253v13C19.832 18.477 18.246 18 16.5 18c-1.746 0-3.332.477-4.5 1.253" /></svg>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800">The WHS Act 2011 (NSW)</h2>
                            <p class="text-sm text-slate-500">The Foundation of Workplace Safety</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <span class="arrow-down transition-transform duration-300 text-slate-500">▼</span>
                </summary>
                <div class="p-6 border-t border-slate-200">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-slate-700">Purpose and Scope</h3>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">The *Work Health and Safety Act 2011* is the primary law that provides the framework to protect the health, safety, and welfare of all workers and other people in NSW workplaces.[4] Its main goal is to protect people from harm by requiring duty holders to eliminate or minimise risks so far as is reasonably practicable.[5]</p>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-slate-700">Key Principles of the Act:</h4>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Primary Duty of Care:</strong> Places the main responsibility for health and safety on the 'Person Conducting a Business or Undertaking' (PCBU).[6]</li>
                        <li><strong>Duties are Not Transferable:</strong> A duty holder cannot contract out of their safety responsibilities.[6]</li>
                        <li><strong>Management of Risks:</strong> Requires risks to be eliminated or, if not possible, minimised so far as is reasonably practicable.[6]</li>
                        <li><strong>Consultation and Representation:</strong> Provides for fair and effective workplace representation, consultation, and cooperation on WHS matters.[5]</li>
                        <li><strong>Enforcement:</strong> Secures compliance through a range of enforcement measures, including notices and prosecutions.[5, 7]</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </details>

            <details class="framework-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm overflow-hidden group">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer bg-white hover:bg-slate-100">
                    <div class="flex items-center">
                        <div class="bg-green-100 text-green-700 rounded-full h-10 w-10 flex items-center justify-center mr-4">
                           <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-6 w-6" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 5H7a2 2 0 00-2 2v12a2 2 0 002 2h10a2 2 0 002-2V7a2 2 0 00-2-2h-2M9 5a2 2 0 002 2h2a2 2 0 002-2M9 5a2 2 0 012-2h2a2 2 0 012 2m-3 7h3m-3 4h3m-6-4h.01M9 16h.01" /></svg>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800">The WHS Regulation 2011 (NSW)</h2>
                            <p class="text-sm text-slate-500">The Detailed Requirements</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <span class="arrow-down transition-transform duration-300 text-slate-500">▼</span>
                </summary>
                <div class="p-6 border-t border-slate-200">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-slate-700">Purpose and Function</h3>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">The *Work Health and Safety Regulation 2011* supports the WHS Act by providing specific and detailed requirements for managing particular hazards and risks.[2] It sets out procedural and administrative requirements, such as the need for licences for high-risk work and record-keeping obligations.[2]</p>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-slate-700">Key Chapters and Areas Covered:</h4>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-2">The Regulation is extensive and covers a wide range of specific workplace situations.[8] Key chapters include:</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Chapter 3 - General Risk and Workplace Management:</strong> Covers duties for facilities, first aid, emergency plans, personal protective equipment (PPE), and managing risks from airborne contaminants and falling objects.[9, 10]</li>
                        <li><strong>Chapter 4 - Hazardous Work:</strong> Details specific rules for noise, hazardous manual tasks, confined spaces, falls, high-risk work licensing, and electrical safety.[8, 11]</li>
                        <li><strong>Chapter 5 - Plant and Structures:</strong> Outlines duties for the safe management, use, and maintenance of machinery, equipment, and structures.[8, 9]</li>
                        <li><strong>Chapter 7 - Hazardous Chemicals:</strong> Sets requirements for classification, labelling, safety data sheets (SDS), registers, placarding, and health monitoring.[8, 12]</li>
                        <li><strong>Chapter 8 - Asbestos:</strong> Provides detailed rules for asbestos management, registers, removal work, licensing, and clearance inspections.[8, 12]</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </details>

            <details class="framework-card bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm overflow-hidden group">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer bg-white hover:bg-slate-100">
                    <div class="flex items-center">
                        <div class="bg-amber-100 text-amber-700 rounded-full h-10 w-10 flex items-center justify-center mr-4">
                            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-6 w-6" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 11H5m14 0a2 2 0 012 2v6a2 2 0 01-2 2H5a2 2 0 01-2-2v-6a2 2 0 012-2m14 0V9a2 2 0 00-2-2M5 11V9a2 2 0 012-2m0 0V5a2 2 0 012-2h6a2 2 0 012 2v2M7 7h10" /></svg>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800">Codes of Practice</h2>
                            <p class="text-sm text-slate-500">Practical, How-To Guidance</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <span class="arrow-down transition-transform duration-300 text-slate-500">▼</span>
                </summary>
                <div class="p-6 border-t border-slate-200">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-slate-700">Purpose and Legal Status</h3>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">A Code of Practice is a practical guide on how to achieve the standards required under the WHS Act and Regulation.[3, 13] They provide detailed information on specific work tasks to make compliance easier.[3]</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Not Mandatory:</strong> Compliance with a Code of Practice is not mandatory. You can use another method as long as it provides an equivalent or higher standard of safety.[14, 15]</li>
                        <li><strong>Admissible in Court:</strong> Approved Codes of Practice are admissible in court proceedings. A court may use a code as evidence of what is known about a hazard and to determine what is 'reasonably practicable' in a given situation.[13, 14, 16]</li>
                        <li><strong>Used by Inspectors:</strong> A SafeWork NSW inspector can refer to a Code of Practice when issuing an improvement or prohibition notice.[14]</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="mt-4 p-4 bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-md">
                        <p class="font-semibold text-amber-900">How to Interpret a Code of Practice [16]:</p>
                        <p class="text-slate-700 mt-1">When reading a code, the language used is important:</p>
                        <ul class="list-inside list-disc mt-2 text-slate-700">
                           <li><strong>'Must'</strong> or <strong>'Requires'</strong> indicates a legal requirement from the Act or Regulation that you must comply with.</li>
                           <li><strong>'Should'</strong> indicates a recommended course of action.</li>
                           <li><strong>'May'</strong> indicates an optional course of action.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </details>

        </main>
    </div>
    
    <script>
        const details = document.querySelectorAll('details');
        details.forEach((targetDetail) => {
            targetDetail.addEventListener("click", () => {
                details.forEach((detail) => {
                    if (detail!== targetDetail) {
                        detail.removeAttribute("open");
                    }
                });
            });
        });
    </script>
